, Gibbings shows that both state and non-state actors engage in transparency, rumours, conspiracies, and surveillance practices. Gibbings reveals that these entangled information practices create suspicion and fear, form new solidarities, and dissolve relationships. Shadow Play is a compelling study that shows that we cannot understand urban projects in post-Suharto Indonesia and the resistance to them without first understanding the complexities embedded in the information practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBusiness and politicszIndonesiazYogyakarta. 0aBusiness relocationzIndonesiazYogyakarta. 0aCity planningxPolitical aspectszIndonesiazYogyakarta. 0aStreet vendorsxGovernment policyzIndonesiazYogyakarta. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aIndonesia.  aSoutheast Asia.  aactivism.  aconspiracy.  ademocracy.  ainformation.  astreet vendors.  athe state.  atransparency.  aurban planning.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073922040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753772240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487537722423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487537722/original  a978-3-11-073922-0  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles